{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_ironsprings_ver01/data/sn84020064/00414217722/1927090401/0550.xml":{"full_text":"FOUR\nGRAND--Matinee Today\nAt 2:00, 4:15, 6:30, 9:00\nU1 /(HA ooi*\" nnM/aiKji iun*\njfkp v ADOLPHE\njg f MENJOU\nn The Ace j\nneMbl\nAlso News and 1 a/,rfNORMAN trevor\n\u201cSEEING THE WORLD,\u201d (Our Gang) Comedy\nPrices 30c\u201420c Children 10c\n111 l 11 1 1\n1 TODAY\nB i. H Adults\nChildren 10c\n\u201cYours To Command\u201d\nWith GEORGE O\u2019HARA\n\u2014also\u2014\n\u201cNOT SO BIG,\u201d and\n\u201cHE FORGOT TO REMEMBER,\u201d Comedy\n\ni.\"'\" \".i'i\" q\nGrand-Tomorrow Night\nAt 6:30-8:45\n5-Acts Association Vaudeville\u2014s\nLeo\u2019s Society Singers\nFeaturing ADELEO MANNA, Coloratura Soprano\nSEBASTIAN LEO, Conductor\nEmily Darrell Faye Thomas\nin in\n\u201cLate for Rehearsal\u201d \u201cMr. Stork\u201d\n\nLOUIS ART C0.,1n\n\u201cJACK THE GIANT KILLER UP TO DATE\u201d\nPresenting\nCapt. Glenn Gulliver, World\u2019s Tallest Giant\nAn Act for Boys and Girls from 4 to 40\nHarry Billie Clark 7\u00b0\"\u2122* screen\nCarl Laemmle presents\nin \u201cBUTTERFLIES IN THE\n\u201cBits of Musical \u2014\\^th\u2014\nLAURA LA PLANTE and\nComedy james kirkwodd\nAdmission'r 50c-25c\nDOUGLAS DAILY DOINGS\nReceives New Cars\nJ. T. Hood has just received a\ncarload of new 52 and 62 model\nChryslers which will be on display\nMonday* c\nTo California\nMiss Le Vaughn- Stumpf* formerly\nemployed ,in the Gadsden cigar stand,\nhas gone to California to make her\nhome in Long Beach.\nJ. G. Miller Buys Chrysler\nJ. G. Miller, who is employed In\nthe P. D. Mercantile company, has\njust, purchased a new Chrysler 52\nsedan from the Hood company.\nHere Front Tucson\nMrs. Paul Doty and Miss Margaret\nDoty are in the city from Tucson.\nThey motored down to attend the\nwedding of Mr. and \"Mrs. Frans\nFairley. Mr. Doty will arrive here\nSunday to pass tl?e day and they\nwill motor home Monday.\nA WHOLE WEEK SPECIAL\nFifty pieces standard merchandise\nat prices never before equalled in\nDouglas. See our window. Sale be\ngins today. Posten-Arthur Hardware\nCo.\u2014Advt.\nA\u2014 r rT A\nA. J* Pickering\nTeacher of Violin and Piano\nStudio 728 Eleventh St.\nj I\nj\nLabor Day\nDANCE\n-SPEER.HALL\nm\n\u2014Given by\u2014\nOrder Railway 'Con\nductors\nElks\u2019 Orchestra\n\nRogers Brolfc\n1 WHERE YOU SAVE\nI Y Vstw' n Groceries, Fruits, Vegetables, Meats\n4 Deliveries Charge Accounts\n/J Y~\" Daily Solicited\nCor. 11th and G Phone 12\nv\nNotice to Subscribers\nThe Circulation department of\nthe Douglas Daily Dispatch re-\nif- quests all subscribers on carrier\nroutes who fail to get their pa- V\npers to notify the Dispatch be-\nfore 9 o\u2019clock in the morning,\nwhen their papers will be deliv\nered at once. More or less delay H\nattends delivery after nine o\u2019clock\ndue to the fact that the regular\nH- delivery force has finished for\nthe day and special service must\nV be depended upon.\n\nRummage Sale\nThe Ladies Aid of Grace Methodist\nchurch- will have a rummage sale\nNovember 4 and 5.\nMoves Studio\nMiss Ida Hickman, teacher of\nniano. has moved her studio from\n742 12th street to 812 11th street.\nTo Texas.\nMiss Isabel Miller will depart to\nday for San Antonio, Texas where\nshe will enter a business school\nthere.\no\nRe-decorate your furniture with* the\nfamous Rogers Lacquer. Easily ap\nplied\u2014quick drying. Douglas Hard\nware Company.\u2014Advt.\no\nSpecial values all this week in Blue\ni Line Chinaware, 10c and 15c per piece,\nj Douglas Hardware Co.\u2014Advt.\n\\gtrn mi\n\nDr. John Cook\n\u25a0j Eye, Ear, Nose and\nThroat Specialist\n1 Has moved his offices from\n1113 G Avenue\n_ to 515 Tenth Street\nPouglas, Arizona\n1 ,i.\n\nDOUGLAS DAILY DISPATCH. SUNDAY MORNING, SEPT. 4, 1927\nwin sew.\nThe ladies of the Methodist church\nwill meet at the home of Mrs.\nGeorge Cowden on Tuesday after\nnoon for the purpose of sewing.\nTo El Paso\nDavid A. Hunter, of this city, has\ngone to El Paso to spend the week- j'\nend with his wife, who is employed\nin the Stone Motor company at El I\nPaso.\nTo Training Camp.\nClayton White has* gone to the\nNew Mexico training camp in the\nWhite mountains. He will remain\nthere until September 13 when he\nwill return for school.\nFood Sale.\nThere will be a cooked food sale'\nheld in Mother\u2019s Place Saturday.\nSeptember tenth. The affair is being\nsponsored by the Auxiliary of the\nBrotherhood of Railway Trainmen.\n\nFrom California.\no. K. Clinton, accompanied by Mrs.\nW. T. Cardwell and her two children\nreturned from California this we\u201ck.\nThey all report a delightful vacation\nand are much improved in health.\nPronrietui- io coast\nE. A. Cota, one of the proprietors\nof the California club in Agua Prieta\nmade a flying trip to the coast the\npast week to attend to matters of\nbusiness and to visit with friends.\nI\nNew Stock\nThe Douglas Furniture and Outfit\nting company has announced that\nthey have received a carload of the\nvery latest and most attractive furni\nture which they are placing on display l\nat their big store on G avenue.\nReturn Here\nMrs. Emma Shedd and Miss Har\nriet Shedd have returned to this\ncity after passing the summer in\nChicago. Mrs. Shedd has purchased\nthe home at 916 12th street and they\nwili make that residence their home.\nAttends University.\nMiss Margaret Sparr will depart\nthe latter part of the week for\nTucson where she will enter the\nUniversity of Arizona for her first\nyear of college work. Miss Sparr\nplans to make jounalism her major I\nsubject.\nFrom Coast\nM. Escobedo, head of various:\nbusiness interests in San Diego, Tia\nJuana, Nogales, Naco and Agua i\nPrieta, accompanied by his associate\n\u201cBlondie\u201d Ortiz spent the past week 1\nin Douglas and Naco looking after j\nhis various interests.\nTo Santa Barbara.\nMiss Aileen Maiden will depart\nTuesday for Santa Barbara, Cali- 1\nfornia where she will attend school.\nMiss Maiden was graduated from\nthe Douglas high shcool last spring i\nand she will continue her school'\nwork in college. i\nTo Tucson.\nMiss Margaret Sweeney will de\npart the latter part of the week for i\nTucson where she will attend the\u2019\nUniversity of Arizona during the en-;\nsuing year. Miss Sweeney, who will be i\na sophomore, attended school at San\nJose, California last year. I\nTo Michigan.\nMiss Rowena Stillman plans to j\ndepart next Sunday for Ann Arbor,'\nMichigan where she will commence!\nher senior year. She was graduated i\nfrom Douglas high school in 1924 j\nand later attended two years of:\ncollege at Occidental in Californ\nia.\nWill Return.\nMiss Frances Richardson, daughter'\nof Mr. 6nd Mrs. E. H. Richardson i\nwho are former residents of this j\ncity, is expected to arrive in Doug\nlas today. She was recently gradu-!\nated from the San Diego State\nTeachers\u2019 college, and will teach at!\nthe Seventh street school this year. I\nIn Douglas\nMrs. A.. F. Van of Empline, Mexico!\nwas in Douglas Saturday as the guest j\nof Mrs. J. M. Johnson. She came to\nthis city to meet her daughter-in- 1\nlaw, Mrs. V. F. Van Ware who was\nenroute to Pilares; the latter who is\nthe daughter of Dr. and Mrs. W.\nTye, \u2022of Pilares, resides in Los!\nAngeles.\nTo Jerome.\nMiss Mabel Mason, who has been!\npassing the summer months here as!\nthe guest of Miss Isabel Miller, has\ngone to Jerome where she will be\nconnected with the city schools. Miss\nMason was graduated from the Doug- i\nlas high school in 1925 and was;\ngraduated this last spring from the!\nTempe Teachers\u2019 College.\nReturn to Douglas.\nThe Misses Carolyn and Fern!\nHalliday, who have been spending 1\nthe summer with their mother and\nbrother in Houston, Texas, returned j\nto Douglas Saturday morning. Dur\ning the summer months they have j\nmade a number of short trips I\nthrough Oklahoma and southern\nTexas.\nVisit At Simonson Home\nBishop Walter Mitchell and the Rev.\nWilliam Cox, rector of the Church of\nthe Holy Comforter, Richmond, Va\u201e j\nvisited the Simonsons this week. Mr.\nCox is an old time friend and fellow I\ncollegian of the bishop of Arizona, and 1\nhas been enjoying many drives about\nthis state from the Santa Fe system\nsouth, and had very pronounced com\npliments for Bisbee and Douglas. i\nGmahling Here.\nWilliam Gmahling has returned to\nthis city following a business trip\nin the eastern part of the state. He\nwill depart the. early part of the\nweek on his xegulaY business trip, and\nleave the latter of week for\nLos Angeles to join Mrs. Gipahling\nwho has been passing the summer\nmonths there. They will both return*\nto their home here the latter part\nof September.\no\nDispatch Telephones 81, 82.\nCULLMR, NOT\nGULLIVER ML\nSHOW AT GRAND\ni\ni.\nI Captain Glenn Culliver is the\nworld\u2019s tallest man.\u00bb He is eight feet\nthree inches tall and weighs 245\npounds. He is appearing at the\ni Grand theater tomorrow night. Born\nj m Ohio, the' son of normally sized\nj parents, Captain Gulliver developed\nthe wanderlust at 17.\nI \u201cBy that I was seven feet\nsix inches fall\u201d Gulliver explained,\n\"and beds had become about the\ni most aggravating tilin'* in mv life\nI I guess I just decided to go out\ninto the world and see if I couldn\u2019t\nfind one lhat fit me/\u2019 So he\ntraveled west, but by the time he\ngot there, he measured eight feet\nand was still growing. \u201cI\u2019d always\nsort of wanted to be a cowboy, and\nI liked it fine, because there was\nplenty of room to sleep out on the\nrange, but the blamed cow ponies\nso small t had to elve it up\u2014\nthey\u2019d run right out from between\n,mv legs,\u2019\u2019 he said. He finally gave\n|up the cowhpy life find developed\nI the system of sleeping half the night\nwith his legs hanging over the foot\n!of the bed, then changing around\nfor the other half and letting his\nhead extend over, pillowing it on the\nseat of a chair. Ringling Brothers\u2019\ncircus proved alluring and for several\nj years he traveled with the show. He\nis 40 years old and has a son and\ndaughter, both well over six feet tall.\nAlthough it\u2019s fun to be able to\nlook over the tops of every one\u2019s\nheads, the life of a giant has its\ndrawbacks, Captain Gulliver claims\u2014\nlor instance, in the matter of going\nthrough doors, climbing ordinary\nI stairways and buying clothing\u2014but\nworst of all is the experience of\ntraveling, and he is doing it all the\ntime! When with Ringlings, he had\na specially arranged car to travel\nin, where he could sleep in peace,\nand there was ho danger of bump\ning his head\u2014but now! Well, a Pull\nj man train was never intended for\nj eight foot, 245 pound men, he says.\n\u201cI tried a lower berth once,\u201d he\nadded, \u201cbut I happened in my sleep\nto pull one leg out of the aisle and\ni bump my knee against the bottom\n!of the other, closing it and almost,\nj smothering and crushing the fellow\ni who was asleep in it. After that I\ndidn\u2019t try any more berths on trains,\nand now just have the porter give\nme a few blankets and roll up and\ngn to sleep in the aisle.\u201d\nI In the same act is Louis Hart, 122\nnonnd strnno- man. who saws: \u201cRight\nnow the human race is busily en\nj gaged in eating itself into the grave.\nHalf the money being spent in Ame:--\ni ica for food could be deposited in\nj the banks where it would provide\nI an income sor\u2019 really ripe old age\u2014\n-1 100 to 150 ye&^s\u2014which would mot\nbe at all improbable if the money\n'were so saved. 11 Fasting, within rea\nson, is not a Vitality destroyer, but\njis the absolute reverse.\u201d Hart has\npracticed his creed with the result\nthat today, in spite of his small\nstature, he has several strength tests\nat which he has challenged the\nworld\u2019s leading strong men and which\nhave never been equalled. To this\nstrength he seems to have actually\nj added the state of eternal youth. \u201cI\nexpect to be young at 100 and live\n'to be at least 150 years old,\u201d ne\nj declared.\nI Hart confines his diet almost en-\nI tirely to vegetables, eating meat but\nj sparringly and infrequently. He con\nsumes a large amount of water. \u201cIt\u2019s\none of the best foods man has yet\ndiscovered\u2014and the beauty of it is\nj it is practically free,\u201d he said, \u201cyet\nI most of us u&e it but sparingly!\u201d\ni So enthusiastic is Hart over the Value\n,of water diet that on several days\n,of each month he makes all three\nI meals of it, yet even on these \u201cfast\u201d\nI days he has no trouble going through\nwith his act\u2014lifting bulky objects\nweighing as much as 500 pounds\ni high above his head, anchoring his\nI heels to the backs of chairs and\nallowing three or four persons to\nI stand on his abdomen and many\nother seemingly miraculous stunts of\nstrength.\nHart is not a naturally born strong\nj man. He is an artist, specializing\n|in ivory miniature portraits. It was\nj while a struggling, puny art student\nin London that Hart decided to \u201cdo\nsbmething for his body.\u201d There were\nseven of the students working in one\nstudio and, finances being short, they\ntook turns acting as models\u2014but Hart\nI was never called upon to act as\nj a model. His skinny little body\nwould not even form the general\nj outline for a masculine study. Sick\n|at heart, he one day began exer\ncising and dieting. A year later\nall the artists in the entire com\nmunity were crying for him to pose\nfor them when they needed a model\nlof classical and powerful physical\nj development.\no\nI JUDGE SAMES\nMAKES TRIP\nTO CHICAGO\nI\nI\ni Judge and Mrs. Albert M. Sames\nof Tombstone will leave Monday\nfor Chicago. They will spend the\nremainder of the month in the\nmiddle west where they will visit\nI relatives in Illinois and lowa,\ni During the absence of Judge\nSames, Judge W. A. O\u2019Connor ol\nNogales will preside in the Cochise\ncounty superior court on Saturday,\nSeptember 10. Judge Gerald Jones\nso Tucson will sit in the Cochise\ncourt on Friday and Saturday,\nSeptember 16 and 17 hearing two\ncases assigned to him at a former\nt Igrm of court and any other court\nbusiness that may come up.\n*\u25a0\u00bb=\u2014rr O\nNo BreakjTist Complete Without\nTllpe\u2018Dispatch.\nEXPORT COPPER\nj DROPS SLIGHTLY\nIN PAST WEEK\nBy CHARLES F. WILLIS,\nEditor, The Mining Journal\n1 The only change in the metal mar\nket during the past week has been the\nlowering oi the export copper price\ni frem 13.65 to 13.50 and the dropping\nl of the lead price from 6.60 to 6.50.\n1 Domestic copper remains at 13.25 and\ni zinc at 6.25. The markets have all\nbeen quiet with comparatively small\nselling and nothing to make it in\nteresting and it will probably remain\nthat way until after the holiday.\nIn spite of the fact all evidence is\nshowing lead to be consumed at a very\nrapid rate, the lead market is dull and\neven the price drop has not stimulat\ned it much. It seefns that the con\nsumers are anticipating a further drop\nin lead prices and are not fulfilling\nthe needs oven though their consump\ntion is great. The advance orders from\ni certain manufacturers Indicate that\nthey expect an unusually large fall\nbusiness.\nSales in zinc have maintained espe\ncially well, stimulated by the drop in\nprice of about ten days ago. The\npurchasing is specified for delivery over\ni the next three months and more of\ni the business is being booked for fu\nture delivery than for immediate.\nMany countries are advancing in\n1 zinc production and contributing to\nthe total of 1,377,257 tons which were\nproduced in 1926. This total is the\n1 largest in history and both 1925 and\n1926 exceeded the war years. Since\n1921 the United States production has\nadvanced from 215,614 tons to 638,533\nj tons, Canada has advanced from 26,-\n494 tons to 61,727 tons, Belgium has\nincreased from 72,917 tons to 209,674\ni tons .France from 26,640 tons to 79,867\ntons, Germany from 29,839 tons to 75,-\n278 tons, upper Silesia from 69,368\ntons to 117,499 tons and numerous\nother countries have advanced sim\nilarly. j\nWhile the present coppes sales are\nslow, there is no decline in actual\ncopper consumption and that which\n1 has been purchased is being rapidly\nused up. Decided activity is expected\nin the copper market in September\nand October as it is known that the\nmanufacturers will have to come in\nto the market to cover requirements\non orders already booked.\nThus the producers are not inclined\nto let loose of any of their copper at\nthe present 13% cent and they\nj are virtually out of the market and\nsitting back in confidence that, by\ni waiting, they can get a better price.\nThe offerings that are making the\npresent price are largely custom smel\nter and second hand copper in small\nlots for immediate delivery.\nThe effect of the lowering of the\n1 export price on copper stimulated for\neign sales and created an interest in\npurchasing. Foreign conditions in\ngeneral are very favorable to the de\nvelopment of a larger chpper business\n1 abroad than we have had for some\ntime.\nRegarding the European copper sit\nuation, Geo. L. Walker writes: \u201cThe\nremalkable change that has come over\nthe European copper market in the\n1 pas tfew weeks is given the following\nseparate explanations hdre: (1) cur\ntailment of production; (2) manipula\ntion by Copper Exporters, Inc.; (3) an\nimproving business outlook; (4) such\nan extreme exhaustion of working\nj supplies that general and heavy buy\ning became obligatory. All of these\nviews are correct, and they should be\nconsolidated. As curtailment of pro\nduction has not yet gone far enough\nto have any effect whatever on sup\nplies, it has exerted only a sentimental\ninfluence. Manipulation by Copper\nExporters has consisted only of the act\nof undermining the manipulative or\ni ganization that previousl yhad con\ntrolled prices. improving business\noutlook could be attested to by pages\nof facts, but it is sufficiently demon\ni strated by statistics which show stead\nily increasing copper consumption and\nsteadily decreasing unemployment in\nthe several European industrial cen\ni ters. That supplies of copper in Eur\nope were reaching a dangerous stage\nof exhaustion has beey pointed out re\npeatedly of late in these advices and\nj supported by statistical proof. The\nj improvement in the copper market\n1 thus has come about purely as a nat\nural consequence of existing condi\ni: tions.\u201d\ni The dividends paid by mining com\n.l panies during August do not reflect\nany depression in the history as the\nj figures for this month are about the\nsame total as during May, the end of\nj the last quarter. The total dividends\nI for August were 16,965,732 as against\n$16,564,931 in May and they are now\ntwo million in excess of the dividends\npaid during August of last year when\n$15,055,853 were disbursed,\ni The mining industry is a long ways\n1 from being down in the depths as\nevery condition, production, consump\ntion .both foreign and domestic) divi\ndends, etc., are in excess of last year.\n1 The only out is that the metal prices\nj are not what they should be for the\nj industry as a whole and the dividend\nPhone Us\nj\nto Call for\ni\nthat \u201cold\u201d Hat, Suit, Frock,\nWrap, Topcoat or any other\nwearable that can be cleaned\ni and renewed.\nHub Tailors\nPhone 544\n529 Eleventh Street\nrecord of the copper mines is main-\ntained by the fact that about 65 per j\ncent of the copper being consumed is j\nbeing produced at a reasonable profit i\nand about 35 per cent is being sold at I\ni cost or at a loss and this is a condi- I\nj tion which cannot be expected to con\ntinue.\n\nDomestic Science At\nFair Expected To Be\nI Better Than Before\ni i\ni\nMrs. E. I. Agnew, chairman of the\ndomestic science department for the\nSeventh Annual Cochise county\nfair reported yesterday that she ex-\npects one of the finest exhibits in l\nher department this year that has\never been seen at the Cochise fair, t\nOne section of the domestic sci-\nence department this year is expect- j\ned to prove .of greater interest than\nany other portion of the fair. This\nsection is to display relics, antiques j\nor anything with a historical inter- j\nest or value.\nThis year through the efforts of 1\nthe head of the department addi\ntional show cases have been secured\nfor this section and these will be I\nkept locked throughout the four\ndays of the fair, September 28, 29,\n1 30 and October 1.-\nj This arrangement will make it'\npossible for persons who have keep- i\nsakes with an historical value at- I\ntached to exhibit them without!\nfear of having them stolen, or in\njured by handling. Mrs. Agnew\nurges that anyone having anything\nworth exhibiting in this department\nmake arrangements at once for the\nentering.\n1 There will be prizes, either cash j\nor merchandise this year for every- I\nthing listed in the premium book-!\nlet for the domestic science depart- J\nment. Last year there was not;\nenough prize money to go around\nand there was some dissatisfaction, j\nThis year the chairman has insist\ned on a proper apportionment of i\nthe prize money so that the do-,\nmestic science department may of- 1\nfer some inducement for the ex- j\nhibitors.\nExhibits for this department will\nbe received at the building on the!\nfair grounds on Saturday and Mon-1\n_ 1 I MIT\u2014\nDon t Miss This\nThe Wonder Bargains of the Year\nBeautiful Imported AQ\nVases\u2014Regular values from 5/0C\n$1.29 to sl.79\u2014 Special this week 1;\nAttractive assortment Of*\nof stationery\u2014Regular value \u00a3%)Q.\n50c box \u2014Special this week\nBuy- your school supplies here\u2014complete stock of\neverything the school boy and girl needs.\nClosed Monday Labor Day from 12 to 6 p. m.\nDouglas Drug Company\n\u201cWhere You Can Get What You Want\u201d\nj\nWHEN BETTER AUTOMOBILES ARE BUILT. BUICK WILL BUILD THEM\nPerfect Comfort--\nJor the woman driver\nAn Adjustable Steering Column\nto Suit Your Convenience\nBuick for 1928 is extremely thoughtful of feminine com*\nfort. One indication of this consideration is Buick\u2019s new\nsteering column, which may be adjusted to the most com*\nsortable position for women, as well as men.\nAnd in addition, Buick for 1928 has a new steering wheel\n\u2014slender to fit feminine fingers \u2014yet deep and solid to\nprovide the firm grip men demand.\nBuick for 1928 pleases women because it is easier to drive\n\u2014because it is njore comfortable to ride in\u2014and because\nit is the acknowledged style-leader among motor cars.\nThat\u2019s why you see so many Buicks at fashionable gather\nings and on the smartest boulevards.\nBUICK MOTOR COMPANY FLINT, MICHIGAN\nDivision es General Motors Corporation\nBUICK>I92B\nGeorge E. Jackson\nSOUTHERN ARIZONA AUTO COMPANY\nDouglas Lowell\nHorse Car Gang\nWill Celebrate\nWith a Picnic\nThe Cochise county voiture of\nthe Forty and Eight congregated\nlast evening in Douglas and held\na confab which resulted in the\nannouncement that the organization\nwill hold a picnic on September 18\nIn Rucker Canyon.\nThere will be a guest list issued\nwhich will include friends of the\norganization from throughout the\ncounty. Plans are to make this pic\nnic a very entertaining affair with\nvarious sports and other attractions\nin addition and plenty of eats.\nday immediately preceding the\nopening of the fair.\no\n7 KILLED; 4 HURT\nYOUNGSTOWN, Ohio, Sept. 3\nSeven persons were shot and killed\nand four others, including a police\nman, were wounded in a shooting\naffray at the home of Tony De\ncapua here tonight, according to re\nports telephoned to police headquar\nters by a Hying squad of patrolmen\nwho answered a riot call at the\nhouse.\nNew Fall Hats\nIn Felts and Felt and\nSatin Combinations\nFor School Girls\nand Girls going to\ncollege\nPopular Prices\nSee our new line of\n\u201cRaggedy Ann\u201d\nFlowers\nThe Unique\nMrs. C. E. Bull\nMrs. C. L. Meloy\n754 G Ave.\nmmd","height":"25005","width":"19461"}}
